Back during the summer, BellSouth offered me a deal consisting of unlimited
local and long distance service, coupled with call waiting and caller ID, for
$39.95 a month. I had been a BellSouth customer for over 30 years, but about
two years ago I had switched to using OneSuite for long distance calls.
OneSuite had the advantage of being dirt cheap, but the convenience of not
having to use an access number appealed to me. I signed up.

What a nightmare it's turned out to be. Every month since, I've had to call up
to inquire why my bill was $60-70 instead of the promised $39.95. We go round
and round. Every month they remove the extra charges and unsubscribe me from
their international plan, which I never asked for to begin with. Every month
there are pending credits. Last month they told me not to be upset with the
bill; that there was actually a credit applied and that I didn't owe them
anything. &quot;At last!&quot;

Yesterday I open the bill (having cancelled the ebill service when it became
apparent that I was going to have to closely examine their charges *every*
month) and find out that I'm past due and owe them $132. Of course, by the time
I open the bill, the business office is closed. I had all night to think (stew)
about it.

I called this morning. The person on the other end had no knowledge of the
$39.95 deal. We went round and round. I got the international plan cancelled
yet again. By the time we were through, I got the bill down to $102, which I
said I would pay. All the extra money it seems goes to &quot;access charges&quot; and
&quot;taxes&quot;. Well, whatever. She told me she could tell me what taxes I already
paid but wasn't allowed to tell me what I'd have to pay next month.

So as I'm getting ready to conclude the call, the woman asks me if I'd be
interested in their DSL service. &quot;Lady&quot;, I said, &quot;there's no way in hell I'd
let you people touch my internet service&quot;. She objected strongly to my use of
&quot;profanity&quot; and started to berate me for using it. That was the first strong
word I'd used in the conversation. I'm sure I wasn't pleasant, but I wasn't
abusive either.

I hung up on her in mid sentence.

I then called Time Warner and signed up for digital phone service: unlimited
local and long distance, plus caller ID, call waiting and call forwarding.
Since I already had cable TV service and Road Runner service, my new monthly
charge will be $101.91... all charges and taxes included, and of course Road
Runner and TV. Everything. In other words, for another $41.57 a month. And
the bill will always be $101.91. We'll see. I hope they're as good as their
word. I do know they don't screw up my internet or TV bills.

Also, with the new telephone number portability law, I don't have to give up my
phone number, which has been the same for almost 20 years.

Tonight I got an automated call asking me to complete a survey with BellSouth
rating my customer support experience today. I didn't bother to call it. I
figure my cancellation should explain my experience with BellSouth more
eloquently than I can... and they won't know about that until the day the Time
Warner guy comes out to the house to install the service for me. Not a word to
BellSouth in the meantime; I can't trust them not to cancel me early or sign me
up for another plan with a 2 year penalty clause for early cancellation.

So sad, too bad. I'm not sorry to see them go.

--
Mortimer Schnerd, RN

