Thanks to Michael Powell and the republican era FCC, the
telcos can pretty much do what they want.

* Tariffed charges override any contract you have signed.
There's lots of court precedent for this. It's not in
dispute in any state.

* The telcos can file new tariffs with no prior notification
other than posting it on a web page.

* The telcos are allowed to recover any fees THEY pay from the
consumer on top of the price of your contracted phone service.

Unfortunately, at least around here, the cable company (yep,
just one) isn't very good either.

Most small businesses probably pay hundreds of dollars extra
every year in bogus charges. We audit our bills frequently
and it's unusual not to find a problem every month (we're an
ISP and get lots of telco bills). We rarely get the same
answer from two different business office reps, and it takes
forever to get credit on overcharges, but they sure threaten
to cut the lines off fast if you don't pay up.

